SWARM INVOCATION RULES:
- Architect MUST review and approve all design decisions before implementation.
- Backend Coder MUST run `cargo test --workspace` after any core/ changes.
- Mobile Executer MUST run platform build verification after any mobile changes.
- Security Auditor MUST review all changes to crypto/, identity/, relay/ modules.
- Fast Executer MUST NOT make changes to crypto algorithms or identity model.
- All roles MUST follow the rules below regardless of model assignment.

================================================================================
§2  CORE ARCHITECTURAL CONSTRAINTS
================================================================================

2.1  DRIFTNET MESH
    - Every node IS the network. No third-party relays, no external servers.
    - Relay = Messaging. Non-negotiable coupling. ON enables relay messaging;
      OFF blocks inbound/outbound relay while local history remains readable.
    - Each new node strengthens the whole. Mycorrhizal routing: dense local
      awareness, thin long-distance highways, demand-driven route formation.
    - Internet is a transport, not a dependency. BLE, WiFi Direct, WiFi Aware,
      and physical proximity are equal transports.

2.2  IDENTITY UNIFICATION
    - `public_key_hex` (Ed25519, 64 hex chars) is the canonical identity for
      persistence and exchange. (PHIL-001)
    - `identity_id` (Blake3 hash of Ed25519 pubkey) and `libp2p_peer_id`
      are DERIVED METADATA — never use as primary key.
    - Identity keys NEVER leave the device.
    - Same Ed25519 key serves both crypto identity and libp2p PeerId.

2.3  RUST CORE DOMINANCE
    - ALL core protocol/security logic lives in Rust core (`core/src/`).
    - Platform adapters (Kotlin/Swift/JS) are thin UI + binding layers that
      call into Rust via UniFFI. They MUST NOT redefine protocol guarantees.
      (PHIL-003)
    - All new code is Rust. No TypeScript, no JavaScript for core logic.
    - `IronCore` (`core/src/lib.rs`) is THE public API surface.
    - `SwarmHandle` (`core/src/transport/`) is the dumb byte pipe.
    - Never bypass IronCore for crypto. All encryption/decryption goes through
      `core.prepare_message()` / `core.receive_message()`.

2.4  PLATFORM PARITY
    - Critical-path behavior MUST be identical across Android, iOS, and
      Web/WASM. (PHIL-006, PHIL-010)
    - UniFFI bindings MUST align with `core/src/api.udl` contract.
    - No temporary lead platform for critical UX behavior.
    - Verification points: relay ON/OFF, identity display/exchange,
      send/receive flow, settings/preferences, error handling.

================================================================================
§3  CRYPTOGRAPHY — NON-NEGOTIABLE
================================================================================

| Layer              | Algorithm              | Notes                              |
|--------------------|------------------------|------------------------------------|
| Identity signing   | Ed25519                | Keys never leave device            |
| Identity hash      | Blake3(ed25519_pubkey) | This is `identity_id`              |
| Key exchange       | X25519 ECDH            | Ephemeral per-message              |
| KDF                | Blake3 derive_key      |                                    |
| Encryption         | XChaCha20-Poly1305     | 24-byte nonce, authenticated       |
| Sender auth        | AAD + Ed25519 sig      | Envelope signature binding         |

NEVER substitute algorithms without explicit owner approval.
Reference types: IdentityKeys, Envelope, Message (core/src/crypto/).

CRYPTO SAFETY RULES:
- Zeroize sensitive data on drop (`zeroize` crate).
- Use constant-time comparisons for secrets.
- NEVER log private keys, seeds, or shared secrets.
- NEVER add crypto dependencies without Security Auditor review.

================================================================================
§4  BUILD VERIFICATION — MANDATORY
================================================================================

ALL code, binding, wiring, or generated code changes MUST be verified with
appropriate build commands before the task is marked complete. Small edits
are NOT exempt.

4.1  RUST CORE
    ```bash
    cargo test --workspace --lib
    cargo clippy --workspace --lib --bins --examples -- -D warnings
    ```
    **Note:** `--lib` flag avoids integration test compilation issues. Full
    `cargo test --workspace` has pre-existing issues:
    - CLI binary type annotation errors fixed by `test = false` in `cli/Cargo.toml`
    - Core integration tests reference unimplemented APIs (ReputationTracker,
      MultiPathDelivery, RelayStats, RetryStrategy) — these are Phase 2+ tests
    - rlib format errors in core integration tests (dependency resolution issue)
    - rustc crash on `test_address_observation.rs` (STATUS_STACK_BUFFER_OVERRUN)
    CLI tests pass: `cargo test -p scmessenger-cli` (20/20 passing).
    Core lib tests pass: `cargo test --workspace --lib` (734/734 passing).
    See PRODUCTION_ROADMAP Phase 1 for full workspace test fix sequence.

4.2  ANDROID
    ```bash
    cd android && ./gradlew assembleDebug
    ```

4.3  iOS
    ```bash
    cd iOS && ./build-device.sh
    ```
    **Windows Constraint (2026-04-11):** iOS build verification is BYPASSED on Windows
    (borrowed laptop). Keep iOS in architectural parity but skip compile/build gates.
    Re-enable when macOS is available again.

4.4  WASM
    ```bash
    cd wasm && cargo build --target wasm32-unknown-unknown
    ```

4.5  FULL SUITE (pre-release)
    ```bash
    cargo fmt --all -- --check
    cargo test --workspace
    cargo clippy --workspace --lib --bins --examples -- -D warnings
    cd android && ./gradlew assembleDebug
    bash ./iOS/verify-test.sh
    cd wasm && wasm-pack build
    bash ./scripts/docs_sync_check.sh
    ```

4.6  FAILURE HANDLING
    If build verification fails, resolve the issue before concluding. Document
    any blockers with the exact failed command and failure reason.

