================================================================================
§11  ESTIMATION RULES
================================================================================

BANNED: Time-based estimates ("2 hours", "30 minutes", "~1 day")
ALLOWED: Lines of Code (LOC) estimates only ("~50 LOC change", "~200 LOC across 3 files")

================================================================================
§12  PROHIBITED ACTIONS
================================================================================

NEVER:
- Decouple relaying from messaging — they are permanently bound
- Introduce third-party relay dependencies (no Nostr relays, no external servers)
- Substitute crypto algorithms without explicit owner approval
- Allow platform-specific protocol drift on critical paths
- Use `unwrap()` in library code
- Add new dependencies without checking existing workspace deps
- Create separate CSS/JS files for web artifacts — single-file only
- Write docs longer than the code they document
- Use time-based estimates in plans or roadmaps
- Treat Web parity as optional before GA
- Allow unbounded local storage growth

================================================================================
§13  KEY DEPENDENCIES
================================================================================

Rust core:
  libp2p 0.53 (tcp, quic, noise, yamux, gossipsub, kad, relay, identify, ping, mdns)
  tokio (full features)
  sled (embedded KV store)
  uniffi (mobile FFI)
  ed25519-dalek 2.1 (signatures)
  x25519-dalek 2.0 (key exchange)
  chacha20poly1305 0.10 (AEAD encryption)
  blake3 1.5 (hashing + KDF)
  bincode (wire serialization)
  serde + serde_json (human-readable)
  parking_lot (fast RwLock)
  zeroize (secure key erasure)
  thiserror + anyhow (error handling)
  tracing + tracing-subscriber (structured logging)
  clap (CLI parsing)

================================================================================
§14  PHILOSOPHY CANON ENFORCEMENT
================================================================================

All work MUST align with `reference/PHILOSOPHY_CANON.md` enforceable rules:

| Rule    | Summary                                      | Criticality    |
|---------|----------------------------------------------|----------------|
| PHIL-001| public_key_hex as canonical identity          | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-002| Relay semantics identical across clients     | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-003| Crypto authority in Rust core only            | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-004| First-run consent gate required               | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-005| Bounded retention policy                     | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-006| Tri-platform parity before GA                 | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-007| Community-operated infrastructure            | negotiable     |
| PHIL-008| English-only alpha, i18n path preserved      | negotiable     |
| PHIL-009| Anti-abuse required before beta               | non-negotiable |
| PHIL-010| No temporary lead platform for critical UX    | non-negotiable |

TRADEOFF PRIORITY (highest to lowest):
1. User trust and security boundaries
2. Reliable delivery and durability
3. Cross-platform interoperability and parity
4. Performance optimization
5. Delivery velocity

================================================================================
§15  INTEGRATION PATTERNS
================================================================================

15.1  SENDING (UI → Network)
    ```rust
    let env = core.prepare_message(recipient_pubkey_hex, text)?;   // IronCore encrypts
    swarm_handle.send_message(target_peer_id, env).await?;         // SwarmHandle transmits
    ```

15.2  RECEIVING (Network → App)
    ```rust
    // On SwarmEvent::MessageReceived:
    let msg = core.receive_message(envelope_data)?;               // IronCore decrypts
    ```

15.3  IDENTITY → NETWORK KEY
    ```rust
    let network_keypair = core.get_libp2p_keypair()?;              // Same Ed25519 key
    let swarm_handle = transport::start_swarm(network_keypair, ...).await?;
    ```

15.4  OUTBOX FLUSH (on PeerDiscovered)
    ```rust
    SwarmEvent::PeerDiscovered(peer_id) => {
        // Check outbox for queued messages to this peer
        // Drain and send via swarm_handle
    }
    ```

15.5  MOBILE/UNIFFI CHANGES
    1. Edit `core/src/api.udl` first (interface definition)
    2. Implement in `core/src/mobile_bridge.rs`
    3. Re-run `uniffi-bindgen` to regenerate Swift/Kotlin stubs

